  "transcript": [
    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 1.2,
      "end": 7.76,
      "text": "This is a labor box recording. All labor box recordings are in the public domain. For",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 7.76,
      "end": 12.3,
      "text": "more information or to volunteer, please visit laborbox.org.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 13.16,
      "end": 16.72,
      "text": "Recorded by Patty McCoy in Hudson, Colorado.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 18.06,
      "end": 25.38,
      "text": "Aesop's Fables, The Hound and the Hair. A young hound started a hair and when he caught",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 25.38,
      "end": 32.7,
      "text": "her up, would at one moment snap at her with his teeth. As though he were about to kill",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 32.7,
      "end": 39.74,
      "text": "her, while at another, he would let go his hold and frisk about her as if he were playing",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 39.74,
      "end": 46.02,
      "text": "with another dog. At last, the hair said, I wish you would show yourself in your true",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 46.02,
      "end": 46.36,
      "text": "colors.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 47.44,
      "end": 53.4,
      "text": "If you are my friend, why do you bite me? If you are my enemy, why do you play with",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-009",
      "start": 53.4,
      "end": 59.32,
      "text": "me? He is no friend who plays double. End of The Hound and the Hair.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
